  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Not every property campaign runs to plan. Sometimes the buyer interest is thinner than expected, sometimes a seller's personal circumstances change, sometimes a building issue surfaces mid-campaign that needs to be resolved before the property can meaningfully transact. In all of these cases sellers start asking the same question: can we just pull the listing and stop? The answer is yes, but the reality is more nuanced than simply asking the agent to take it down. Withdrawing a listing in Queensland carries legal, financial, and perception consequences that are worth understanding before you make the call.</p>

      <p>This article walks through when it makes sense to withdraw, what the Form 6 authority actually commits you to, the real costs of pulling a listing, the difference between marking a property 'off the market' and fully terminating the agency, and how long you should wait before relisting if you plan to come back.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why sellers withdraw listings</h2>
      <p>Withdrawals tend to fall into four broad categories. The first is a campaign that is not generating serious buyer interest. After two to four weeks of open homes and marketing, the pool of prospective buyers is shallow, the offers are well below expectation or non-existent, and the seller is losing confidence that the current strategy is going to produce a result. The second is a change in the seller's personal circumstances: a relationship breakdown, a health issue, a job loss or relocation, or a change in plans for where the household is going next. The third is a market shift during the campaign, where interest rates move, sentiment softens, or a comparable sale prints well below expectation and the seller prefers to wait out the change rather than transact into weakness. The fourth is a material issue that has emerged on the property itself: a building and pest report that has flagged something significant, a body corporate dispute, a neighbour's development application, or a title issue that needs to be resolved before the property is genuinely saleable.</p>

      <p>Each of these reasons is legitimate. Withdrawal is not an admission of failure, it is a decision about whether the current campaign is the right vehicle for the current conditions. What matters is that the decision is made deliberately, with a clear understanding of what it costs and what comes next, rather than as a panicked reaction to a soft second weekend of opens.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The legal position: the Form 6 authority</h2>
      <p>In Queensland, a seller appoints an agent to sell their property by signing a Form 6 Appointment of Property Agent. The Form 6 is the legal contract that governs the agent's authority to act on behalf of the seller. It sets out the agent's term, commission, any marketing contribution, the conditions under which the authority can be terminated, and what happens if a buyer introduced during the campaign later purchases the property. Most Form 6 authorities for residential sales run for a fixed exclusive term of 60 to 90 days, sometimes longer for higher-value or unusual properties. During this period the agent has exclusive rights to market and sell the property, meaning the seller cannot list with another agent, and cannot typically terminate the authority at will.</p>

      <p>To withdraw the listing while the Form 6 is still running, you need to either negotiate an early release with the agent's principal, or wait out the term before moving on. Any fees, termination provisions, and the treatment of introduced buyers will all be set out in the Form 6 you signed, which is why reading it carefully before you sign, and again before you withdraw, is worth the time.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What withdrawing actually costs</h2>
      <p>The financial cost of a withdrawn campaign usually falls into three buckets. The first and most common is vendor-paid advertising. Photography, drone work, floor plans, portal listings on realestate.com.au and domain.com.au, signboards, social media, and print advertising are almost always non-refundable. If you have committed to a $6,000 marketing package and the campaign has been live for three weeks, that money is gone regardless of whether the property sells, withdraws, or sits. The second is any termination fee the Form 6 may allow the agent to charge if you pull the listing before the end of the fixed term. The third is the ongoing commission right: if a buyer introduced to the property during your campaign later purchases it within the period specified in the Form 6, typically 60 to 180 days after termination, the agent may still be entitled to commission even though the sale completes after you withdraw.</p>

      <p>These costs are not a reason to avoid withdrawing a campaign that is genuinely failing. They are a reason to take the decision seriously, and to explore whether a price adjustment, a strategy change, or an extended campaign could produce a better outcome before you pull the plug.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The right way to withdraw</h2>
      <p>If you have decided to withdraw, the clean path is to have the conversation with your agent first. A good agent will already have a read on whether the campaign is recoverable and may offer alternatives: a revised price guide, a shift from auction to private treaty, a pause on portal visibility while presentation is improved, or a pivot to a different target buyer. These are often worth considering before you formally end the engagement. If after that conversation you still want to withdraw, put it in writing to the agency's principal or licensee, reference the Form 6, and request written confirmation of the termination, any fees outstanding, and the period during which the agent retains a commission right over introduced buyers.</p>

      <p>If the Form 6 term has expired, termination is typically straightforward. If the term is still current, expect some negotiation: a reasonable agent will usually agree to release a seller whose circumstances have genuinely changed, particularly where the relationship has broken down. Most disputes over Form 6 terminations come down to one of two things: the seller did not read the authority before signing, or the agent has not managed the campaign well and is reluctant to acknowledge it. Getting independent legal advice before terminating a Form 6 costs a few hundred dollars and is worth it for any sale above a few hundred thousand.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">'Off the market' is not the same as terminated</h2>
      <p>One of the most useful middle options in Queensland is to mark the property 'off the market' on the portals while keeping the Form 6 in place. Realestate.com.au and domain.com.au both support this. The listing stops appearing in fresh search results and day-count displays, the open homes pause, and the public-facing campaign effectively ends. But the agent still holds the authority, the relationship continues, and the property can be brought back onto the market quickly if circumstances change or a specific buyer re-engages. This is a useful tool when the seller needs a pause rather than a termination: a holiday period, a short-term change in plans, or time to address a specific issue. It is not a way to avoid commitment to your agent, it is a pragmatic pause that both sides can agree to when the campaign needs a breather.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When to relist, and how the market will perceive you</h2>
      <p>Portals remember. Buyers and buyer's agents can see how long a property has been on the market, how many times it has been relisted, and whether the price has been adjusted. A listing that is withdrawn and then relisted within a few weeks tends to be treated by the buying market as a continuation of the same campaign, which means the days-on-market counter in buyer perception keeps running even if the portal counter resets. If you relist too soon, you carry all of the perception baggage of the first campaign into the second one, without the benefit of a fresh read.</p>

      <p>A meaningful gap of 60 to 90 days between a terminated campaign and a relist tends to reset buyer perception in most inner Brisbane suburbs. Longer is better if the property has significant baggage: high-profile price adjustments, publicly passed-in auctions, or a well-known issue such as a building dispute. The relist also needs to be a genuinely different campaign: new photography, a different price strategy, potentially a different agent, and a clear narrative for why it is back on the market. Relisting the same property at the same price with the same photos after 30 days is close to guaranteed to produce a worse result than the original campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>
      <p>Withdrawal is a legitimate tool, but it is not free. Before you pull a listing, ask three questions. First, is this a strategy problem (wrong price, wrong method, wrong agent) that can be fixed without terminating, or is it a situation problem (changed circumstances, market shift, property issue) that genuinely requires a pause? Second, what does the Form 6 actually commit you to, and what fees or commission rights will survive the termination? Third, what is your plan for coming back: when, at what price, with what new information, and with what kind of gap in between?</p>

      <p>If you have good answers to all three, withdrawal can be the right call. If you are pulling the listing because the first two opens were slow and you are anxious, step back and ask whether a two-week extension and a price conversation would be the better use of the next fortnight. Most campaigns that fail do so not because they were launched in the wrong month, but because they were priced a little high, prepared a little hastily, or given up on a little early. Understanding when a withdrawal is justified, and when it is just impatience in disguise, is one of the more valuable calls a seller can make.</p>

